            <pb n="3" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Growth of the Dry Land.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The following<lb break="yes"/>are the results of the investigations which
                    have had<lb break="yes"/>for their object the determination of the extent of
                        the<lb break="yes"/>dry land at different epochs. In the most ancient<lb
                        break="yes"/>times&#x2014;during the silurian, devonian, and carbonifer-<lb
                        break="no"/>ous epochs, and even as lately as the triassic period&#x2014;<lb
                        break="yes"/>the portion of the surface supporting land vegetation<lb
                        break="yes"/>was exclusively insular. At a subsequent epoch, these<lb
                        break="yes"/>islands became connected with each other, forming<lb
                        break="yes"/>numerous lakes and deeply-indented bays. Finally,<lb
                        break="yes"/>when the mountain chains of the Pyrenees, the Ap-<lb break="no"
                    />penines, and the Carpathians, were elevated&#x2014;about<lb break="yes"/>the
                    epoch, therefore, of the olden tertiary formations<lb break="yes"/>&#x2014;the
                    great continents possessed nearly their present<lb break="yes"/>form and extent.
                    During the silurian epoch, when the<lb break="yes"/>cycade&#x00E6; were in the
                    greatest abundance, and the gi-<lb break="no"/>gantic saurians were living, the
                    whole surface of dry<lb break="yes"/>land from pole to pole must have been less
                    than it<lb break="yes"/>now is in the Pacific and Indian oceans. We shall<lb
                        break="yes"/>see presently how this great ponderance of oceanic<lb
                        break="yes"/>surface must have contributed, together with other<lb
                        break="yes"/>causes, to equalize climates, and to maintain a high<lb
                        break="yes"/>temperature. It is only necessary to add here, in<lb
                        break="yes"/>reference to the progressive extension of dry land,<lb
                        break="yes"/>that a short time before the cataclysms which, at<lb
                        break="yes"/>longer or shorter intervals, caused the destruction<lb
                        break="yes"/>of so many gigantic vertebrated animals, part of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>continental masses presented the same divisions as at<lb
                        break="yes"/>present. There prevails, both in South America and<lb
                        break="yes"/>in Australia, a great analogy between the living ani-<lb
                        break="no"/>mals and the extinct species of those countries. Fos-<lb
                        break="no"/>sil species of kangaroo have been discovered in New<lb
                        break="yes"/>Holland; and in New Zealand, the semi-fossilized<lb break="yes"
                    />bones of a gigantic struthious bird, the dinornis of<lb break="yes"/>Owen,
                    closely allied to the present apteryx, of the<lb break="yes"/>same islands, and
                    remotely so to the recently extinct<lb break="yes"/>dodo of the island of
                        Rodriguez.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt&#x2019;s Voyages.</hi>
                </p>
